WHAT IS THIS FILE
The certified display profile for the Apple Pro Display XDR. It defines
the 32-inch IPS LCD panel with 6016 × 3384 resolution, 10-bit true color,
peak brightness (1600 nits HDR highlights, 1000 nits sustained full screen),
factory-calibrated Reference Modes (HDTV Video, HDR Video, Digital Cinema,
Photography, Internet & Web), and the EOTF and gamut parameters for each
mode. This file is the single source of truth for GIOP ODTs targeting the
Pro Display XDR.

WHY IT EXISTS
The Pro Display XDR is a widely used mastering and reference monitor in
design, photography, and independent filmmaking. Its multiple Reference
Modes define precise color spaces and EOTFs. Without this certified profile,
an ODT may not correctly activate the right mode or may exceed the display's
sustained luminance limits. This file provides the auditable model.

HOW IT WORKS
This file specifies:
  1. Panel technology and native characteristics.
  2. The five Reference Modes, each with primaries, white point, EOTF,
     and peak luminance.
  3. Factory calibration and Delta-E guarantee.
  4. Interface (Thunderbolt 3) and its impact on signal format.
  5. GIOP ODT configuration per mode.

WHERE IT IS DEPLOYED
- Color grading suites (DaVinci Resolve, Final Cut Pro)
- VFX review (Nuke)
- Photography and print proofing (Photoshop, Lightroom)
- Design studios.

WHO USES IT
- L3 GIOP Colorists (primarily independent and boutique post houses).
- L2 GIOP Engineers: configure ODTs for Pro Display XDR.
- Calibration technicians.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Ensures that the exact Reference Mode settings (primaries, EOTF, peak
luminance) are known to the GIOP ODT, eliminating mode mismatch errors.
Provides the sustained vs. peak luminance distinction, which is critical
for grading HDR content that must not exceed 1000 nits full-screen.

1. PANEL TECHNOLOGY
  Type             : IPS LCD with direct backlight (576 blue LEDs)
  Resolution       : 6016 × 3384 (20.4 million pixels)
  Screen Size      : 32 inch (diagonal)
  Pixel Pitch      : 0.116 mm
  Bit Depth        : 10-bit (true 10-bit, no FRC)
  Native Contrast  : ~1,000,000:1 (with local dimming)
  Backlight        : 2D array of 576 individually controlled zones
                     (local dimming for HDR contrast)

2. REFERENCE MODES
   The Pro Display XDR provides factory-calibrated Reference Modes. Each
   mode sets primaries, white point, EOTF, and peak luminance to match a
   specific imaging standard.

   Mode 1: HDTV Video (BT.709)
     Primaries   : BT.709 (sRGB/Rec.709)
     White Point : D65
     EOTF        : BT.1886 (gamma 2.4)
     Peak Luminance : 100 cd/m² (user-adjustable)
     Use Case    : SDR broadcast and web video.

   Mode 2: HDR Video (P3-ST.2084)
     Primaries   : DCI-P3
     White Point : D65
     EOTF        : ST.2084 (PQ)
     Peak Luminance : 1000 cd/m² (sustained full screen),
                      1600 cd/m² (peak highlights, up to 25% of screen)
     Use Case    : HDR mastering for cinema and streaming.

   Mode 3: Digital Cinema (P3-DCI)
     Primaries   : DCI-P3
     White Point : D63 (DCI white)
     EOTF        : Gamma 2.6 (pure power, approximately 48 cd/m² reference)
     Peak Luminance : 48 cd/m² (nominal, for cinema projection emulation)
     Use Case    : Digital cinema grading preview.

   Mode 4: Photography (P3-D65)
     Primaries   : DCI-P3
     White Point : D65
     EOTF        : Gamma 2.2
     Peak Luminance : 100 cd/m² (adjustable)
     Use Case    : Still photography and print proofing.

   Mode 5: Internet & Web (sRGB)
     Primaries   : sRGB (BT.709)
     White Point : D65
     EOTF        : sRGB (approximately gamma 2.2 with linear toe)
     Peak Luminance : 100 cd/m² (adjustable)
     Use Case    : Web graphics and UI design.

   All modes support user fine-tuning of luminance and white point.

3. FACTORY CALIBRATION
   Calibration Method:
     Each display is individually characterised at the factory using a
     spectroradiometer and a 3D LUT.
   Accuracy:
     ΔE < 1.0 (average) against the target Reference Mode, measured
     across a 33-patch test chart.
   Calibration Data:
     Stored in the display's firmware. The host OS (macOS) automatically
     selects the correct ICC/ColorSync profile.

   For GIOP, an ODT targeting the Pro Display XDR must read the active
   Reference Mode from macOS metadata (or be manually set) and configure
   the output primaries, EOTF, and peak luminance accordingly.

4. INTERFACE
   Connection       : Thunderbolt 3 (USB-C)
     - Provides power (up to 96W to host laptop).
     - Carries DisplayPort 1.4 signal (for video).
     - Carries USB 3.1 data (for calibration and firmware updates).
   Signal Format    : 6016 × 3384 @ 60 Hz, 10-bit 4:4:4 RGB
     (Dual-link SST via two DP streams over Thunderbolt).
   Additional Ports : 3x USB-C (USB 3.1 Gen 1) on the monitor for
                      peripherals.

5. GIOP ODT RECOMMENDATION
   For each Reference Mode, the GIOP ODT target is:
     - HDTV Video: scene-linear → BT.709 primaries → BT.1886 EOTF (100 nit).
     - HDR Video : scene-linear → ACES RRT+ODT for P3-D65 PQ 1000 nit.
     - Digital Cinema: scene-linear → DCI-P3 D63 gamma 2.6 (48 nit).
     - Photography: scene-linear → P3-D65 gamma 2.2 (100 nit).
     - Internet & Web: scene-linear → sRGB EOTF (100 nit).

   The ODT shall respect the peak luminance limit: no frame shall have a
   full-screen average exceeding 1000 nit (HDR mode) or the specified SDR
   luminance.

